  "prompt": "What is the definition of current?",
  "response": "In physics and electrical engineering, **current** refers to the flow of electric charge through a conductor or space. It is typically measured in **amperes (A)**, which represent the amount of charge passing a given point per unit of time.\n\nMathematically, current (\\( I \\)) is defined as:\n\n\\[\nI = \\frac{\\Delta Q}{\\Delta t}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( \\Delta Q \\) is the change in electric charge (in coulombs, C).\n- \\( \\Delta t \\) is the change in time (in seconds, s).\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Direction of Current**: Conventional current is defined as the flow of positive charge, even though in most cases (e.g., metals), the actual charge carriers are negatively charged electrons moving in the opposite direction.\n2. **Types of Current**:\n   - **Direct Current (DC)**: Flows in one direction only, typically from a battery or DC power supply.\n   - **Alternating Current (AC)**: Changes direction periodically, as in household electricity.\n3. **Current in Circuits**: In an electrical circuit, current is driven by a voltage (potential difference) and is influenced by the resistance of the conductor (Ohm's Law: \\( V = IR \\)).",
